\begin_layout Title
Status consumption and intertemporal substitution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract

\shape italic
Status consumption is known to be ubiquitous but the role of wealth inequalities
 in status consumption is less understood in the varied contexts of developing
 countries.
 We develop a model for status consumption based on the intertemporal consumer
 choice where status is viewed as part of the consumer's utility.
 The utility function used in the model comprises of both quality in non-durable
 consumption and owned durable goods.
 Using the data on durable goods ownership available in the Tanzanian LSMS
 consumption microdata, we discuss how a segregation of quality may characterise
 status consumption in a developing economy..
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recent research suggests an ubiquity of status-related consumption and the
 relevance of peer effects in consumer demand 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019,KausSA,ZahraIndia,JaikumarConspConIneq,FrieheGermany"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 One expects therefore that regardless of how poor an economy is, the consumers
 would maintain a consumption level relative to their reference group level.
 Since reference groups are subject to spatial and economic segregation,
 it follows that the disproportionate demand for signaling-goods (i.e.
 conspicuous consumption) would depend on the age-composition of the consumer
 population and the degree of social segregation.
 An insufficient communication amongst the reference groups imposed by region
 or social barriers could create reference groups so apart that the demand
 for conspicuous goods completely absent for some significant reference
 groups.
 In other words, if the poor in an economy are far too many, the poor majority
 may neither observe nor emulate the lifestyles of a rich microscopic minority.
 Such dependence of status consumption on poverty levels has been only partly
 explored by the studies on effects of income inequality on conspicuous
 consumption 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq,Duesenberry1949,ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Friehe et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrieheGermany"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who observe visible consumption in the regions of erstwhile East and West
 Germany after the economic liberalisation at the end of cold war to test
 if prolonged measures of suppressed incomes can influence visible consumption
 when the incomes rise with economic changes.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking a slightly different approach in this chapter, we view status consumption
 as a combination of expensive durable goods and high-quality non-durable
 consumption - comparing the two amongst consumers spread across different
 age-groups and levels of urbanisation.
 To endogenise the role of long-term durable goods and personal characteristics
 in status, we use an intertemporal model of consumer choice where both
 quality of consumption and long-term goods contribute to the consumer utility
 which is inclusive of status.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That consumers compete in a social order by displaying their owned items
 and quality consumption - is based on a social deference based view of
 status that has been embraced in many economic studies 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy,corneo_snobbism,ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 .
 If we can agree that the role of status consumption is to influence such
 a ranking, it follows that the status for a consumer with a fixed set of
 personal characteristics can only be improved either with quality in non-durabl
e consumption or with long-term durable goods (i.e.
 durable goods that can be part of inter-generational transfers).
 If the long-term durable goods are typically accumulated over generations,
 it follows that the demand for quality in non-durable consumption would
 be driven by a certain myopia relative to that for durable goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The sense of quality in the conventional demand analyses is often interpreted
 from an aggregation of items over commodities as separable groups
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity,McKelveyQuality2011,McKenzie2005,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,DongShonkwierCappsQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 As the theoretical requirements for such an aggregation require a detailed
 set of market prices of goods within every commodity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,NelsonQualityQuantity"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, the view of status consumption as high-quality consumption is often hampered
 with a lack of information on brand/type variety in the typical consumption
 survey.
 The studies on conspicuous consumption can circumvent this issue by focusing
 on a particular instance of status consumption - comprising of (visible)
 goods that are meant to be futile for the general needs of the consumer.
 The futility of status goods ensures the separability of demand for visible
 goods - and views a narrowed context of quality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We argue that the futility assumption cannot be made in severely unequal
 societies where wealth differences may be far too wide to be narrowed with
 visible (or high quality) non-durable consumption.
 As status consumption comprises both of quality across commodities and
 ownership of durable goods, the contribution of durable goods to the ranking
 order might dominate any changes with visible (high quality) non-durable
 consumption.
 Evaluating the above framework in the particular case of Tanzania, we discuss
 how quality in non-durable consumption could be segregated by long-term
 characteristics (e.g.
 such as education of parents) and availability of certain durable goods.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We hope that the framework with quality and durable goods with life-cycle
 effects that can used to test the significance of status consumption in
 an economy.
 A refinement of status consumption is particularly needed in the developing
 economies where both wealth differences and social segregation are relatively
 higher.
\end_layout

