\begin_layout Standard
Status consumption was notably elaborated by Veblen 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 in his 1899 treatise titled 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Theory of the Leisure Class
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Around the time when Marx had endorsed a view of all commodities as products
 of labour (diamond and corn alike), Veblen seemed to have explored the
 psychological basis for consumption among the economic classes.
 At times, his view of status consumption may appear critical of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bourgeois
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 wastefulness 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Throughout the entire evolution of conspicuous expenditure, whether of goods
 or of services or human life, runs the obvious implication that in order
 to effectually mend the consumer’s good fame it must be an expenditure
 of superfluities.
 In order to be reputable it must be wasteful.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 - but Veblen hardly dwells upon the equivalence of labour for exchange
 of commodities.
 While he marks the tendency amongst the elite to distance themselves from
 physical labour - he argues that this tendency has transformed itself into
 a desire of displaying exploits and has survived in the culture from more
 primitive hunter-gatherer and agrarian societies.
 This symbolism - he argued - is inherent in all exchange of goods and services
 (including devotion and education 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

The adoption of the cap and gown is one of the striking atavistic features
 of modern college life, and at the same time it marks the fact that these
 colleges have definitely become leisure-class establishments, either in
 actual achievement or in aspiration.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "VeblenLeisureClass"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assisted with the developments in game theory and an improvement in the
 quality of microdata from consumption surveys, an interest in Veblen's
 observations has been revived in the recent years (see Frank 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond,FrankModel"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Hirsch 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "HirschSocialLimits"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Koustobinas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KoutsobinasStatusPoliticalEconomy"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 The recent attention to status consumption - however - should not to be
 viewed asunder from the consumer demand literature on habit-formation (see
 for example Muellbauer 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MuellbauerRationalityMyopia1988."
literal "true"

\end_inset

's discussion of the myopia amongst consumers and Fisher-Shell
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for the classical treatment of quality and cost-of-living indices).
 It is possible to view status consumption in the intertemporal framework
 with life-cycle assumptions as a generalised inertia in moving away from
 a state of higher quality - a tendency that may in turn be determined by
 the long-term characteristics (such as social identity or education).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The relevance of social identities in consumption habits has been a common
 theme of much of the literature in conspicuous consumption (see Chao et
 al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Charles et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Omori et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "OmoriSmithVisRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, Kaus
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"
literal "true"

\end_inset


\series bold
 
\series default
and Khamis et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 The literature on marketing also finds the role of durable goods ownership
 in a formation of identities (see Corneo 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 We believe it is possible to link the two threads - of identity and habit
 formation - if the role of social identity and ranking could be endogenised
 in an intertemporal setting with a substitution between the consumer's
 long-term and short-terms goals.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simple view of status in the intertemporal substitution is one where it
 is a long-term concern for the consumer.
 This is aligned with the how status is usually viewed in the sociology
 and health studies literature (see Michelson et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MichelsonMunizDeRose2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Psake et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PsakiSeidman2013"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for a few examples).
 However, if status were only accumulated over long-term, there would be
 no utility from status consumption in the intertemporal framework.
 The seeming paradox is easily resolved with an approach that has been used
 by Coleman
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ColemanSocialTheory1990"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 and Corneo et al 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "corneo_snobbism"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 - who view status as a ranking order of consumers based on their incomes
 that can be altered with consumption.
 In other words, a consumer achieves status utility through status consumption
 by moving herself up in a ranking order that is otherwise determined by
 wealth and income.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such a formulation of status consumption also reminds us to exercise caution
 when looking at items in the developing countries that are considered 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the developed countries.
 As the relative wealth differences are more relevant for status differences
 in the developing countries where industrial development is concentrated
 into fewer urban areas, the wealth differences could have far more weight
 for status than the limited range of visible items available to a consumer
 in the developing world
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 for criticism of a certain 
\shape italic
belle epoque 
\shape default
view of status consumption.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 This caveat on the relevance of wealth differences is not highlighted enough
 in the literature on conspicuous consumption we have surveyed (except for
 some studies directly exploring the effect income inequality on conspicuous
 consumption with exogenously observed poverty/income levels or GINI indices
 - see Jaikumar 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "JaikumarConspConIneq"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 Some studies, for example, include long-term durable goods (e.g.
 housing) in status-related consumption while others choose to focus on
 non-durable consumption.
 An empirical view assisted with the intertemporal framework helps us assess
 whether particular long-term durable goods should be viewed as part of
 status consumption or not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given that status competitions are always relevant in one's own reference
 group, status consumption varies across several social strata - particularly
 in the developing countries where the wealth differences are wide.
 While the economic history of the developing world might suggest that lower
 classes tend to emulate the habits of past upper economic classes (see
 Timothy
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

), the overwhelming evidence for status consumption at finer levels marks
 the relevance of one's own reference group (see Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Chai
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 One possibility that hasn't been explored enough at the finer levels of
 consumption is that the visible goods too could vary significantly across
 the social strata.
 A luxury watch - for example - may be as useful as its pawned value in
 the poorest sections of a developing economy.
 That a common set of visible goods should be considered relevant for all
 participants in a consumer survey could therefore be subject to debate.
 One one hand, it could be argued that rapid industrialisation and a transformat
ion of consumer markets in many developing countries has resulted in a narrowing
 of income differences and creation of new markets for status (see Srinivas
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SrinivasSanskritization"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Ustuner-Holt
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "UstunerHolt2010"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 , Burke 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "TimothyBurkeLifebuoyMen1996"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and Wisman 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WismanSavingClassIdentity2009"
literal "false"

\end_inset

) where every consumer can spend on the same set of visible items.
 The measurement of visible consumption would therefore sufficiently capture
 the essence of all status consumption.
 On other other hand, it could also be argued that despite recent economic
 developments, wide social inequalities have prevailed in the populations
 in both Asia and Africa and that the relevance of severe and widespread
 income inequalities on what may constitute status consumption cannot be
 fully discarded (see Khamis et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ZahraIndia"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The questions in the consumer survey (which is how a researcher may obtain
 the list of visible items) may need to be adjusted to include items that
 may indicate wealth.
 This is because the criteria of what items are of visible importance is
 not enough for identifying status consumption in an environment where wealth
 differences are both wide and visible.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 ).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A model for the combined effect of wealth and consumption on one's status
 thus becomes necessary to address the relevance of wealth differences in
 status consumption across varied cultural contexts.
 In a developing economy, the measure of wealth and income can be proxied
 relatively easily with the stock of durable goods the consumer has (inclusive
 of housing, land and other long-term assets) so that durable consumption
 contributes directly to the ranking order.
 The contribution of non-durable consumption - on the other hand - would
 be only through the quality of non-durable consumption.
 We argue that if a common set of consumer needs makes sense in the population
 being observed, then there is no status utility to be achieved through
 addressing of needs.
 This is because the consumer with a habit of 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
high-quality in consumption (or deriving higher felicity above the fulfillment
 of needs) would 
\shape italic
ceteris paribus 
\shape default
have higher status than another consumer consuming less quality.
 The fulfillment of consumer needs - which are the same for every one by
 definition - does not carry a similar influence on status.
 Thus if there is any status related utility to be derived from non-durable
 consumption, it would be constituted in the felicity from 
\shape italic
relative 
\shape default
quality (which is defined as distance from needs observed within a particular
 reference group).
 It also follows that any status that is not signaled with quality in non-durabl
e consumption must come out of long-term durable goods (i.e.
 the proxy of wealth).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The measurement of ownership of long-term durable goods is relatively easier
 - if we consider long-term durable goods as only those that can be passed
 on by the consumer to the next generation (this has implications in the
 life-cycle model as we later elaborate).
 The short-term concerns of the consumer (which could themselves be influenced
 by the acquired wealth) comprise only of needs and quality (inclusive of
 short-term durable items - if any) which both determine the non-durable
 consumption by the consumer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An appropriate measure of quality is therefore key to our empirical analysis.
 Since the consumption surveys hardly obtain brand-related details of the
 item, one must rely on alternative ways to distinguish higher than required
 consumption from a minimum necessary consumption.
 In much of the consumer demand literature on quality, for example, the
 measurement of quality relies on detailed market prices.
 If market prices are observed (as is often the case for food), quality
 is simply the proportion of expensive items standardised by quantity
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity,DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,GibsonKimQualityBog2019,McKelveyQuality2011"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 When quantities consumed and the details prices aren't available, a notion
 of quality can rely on the cost of a standard basket of basic needs ( i.e.
 the problem of cost-of-living indices - see Fisher 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FisherShell1968"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 A measure of quality is thus simply the expenditure in 
\shape italic
excess 
\shape default
of the cost of needs
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Since most empirical data is gathered at household levels, the larger households
 having more needs would require the consumption data to be scaled by the
 number of members - thus standardising the needs across households.
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Our notion of quality thus in turn relies on a sound definition of basic
 needs - which provide the reference point for quality in the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the cost of needs as a reference point, the very idea that there are
 universal needs has been a somewhat contentious issue.
 Again on one hand, we have the view that needs are determined solely by
 subjective preferences (see Townsend
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) while on the other, there is the view that a common man's needs can supersede
 her subjective interests (wants).
 We have leaned towards an objective middle-path proposed by Doyal and Gough
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 who consider autonomy itself - in addition to health - as a basic need
 of the consumer without shunning the idea that the needs across cultural
 contexts should be standardised.
 The basic needs of the consumer are the standard requirements not meeting
 which would lead to a definite harm (this is in accordance to the theory
 argued for by Doyal and Gough 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DoyalGoughNeeds1991"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 To an argument that a family can survive on just starch, for example, the
 counter-argument would be that a foreseeable damage to the health of the
 consumer incurred by not having other nutrients is definite.
 A starch diet fulfilling the set of dietary needs can thus be ruled out.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Such an objective assessment of basic needs could also enrich the discussion
 on status consumption in the literature which often performs a rather subjectiv
e assessment of consumer necessities.
 Despite relying on the futility assumption (i.e.
 that conspicuous consumption is necessary futile), the empirical studies
 in status consumption tend to make varied assumptions about what to include
 as part of conspicuous consumption and what not to.
 The contents of the consumer basket for conspicuous consumption often include
 items that are just commonly understood to have some signaling value (jewelry
 etc.
 that were first identified by Charles et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "CharlesHurstRace"
literal "true"

\end_inset

).
 It is common in the literature to use a consumer basket identified from
 a different economy on the basis of items being of conspicuous value by
 common knowledge.
 A consideration of health and autonomy could provide an appropriate justificati
on for the futility of conspicuous consumption in a particular economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
That said the ideas of health and autonomy are somewhat subject to interpretatio
n in a particular context.
 In the LSMS survey data we use for Tanzania, for example, we treat the
 costs incurred by owning durable goods as part of needs only if the durable
 goods themselves are part of needs.
 The costs that the owner of a refrigerator or a large house (let's say)
 has to bear can only be part of basic needs if the durable goods themselves
 are a basic need.
 In the particular case of Tanzania, refrigerator isn't deemed a basic need
 while housing is.
 The other empirical issue with the measurement of quality is that certain
 maintenance costs for own durable goods may appear as non-durable consumption
 in the diary (we revisit this issue in detail in Section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While needs may serve as a necessary reference point for our notion of quality,
 the more relevant reference point for status consumption is consumer's
 group or regional identity.
 If the choice consumer faces is to either save for future or spend on status
 goods, she is likely to be concerned with the rich consumption in her immediate
 social surroundings rather than a distant (possibly richer) consumer.
 The factors of locality are thus relevant for the measurement of contribution
 to status utility from consumption
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Notice that even if the prices of needs are considered in two different
 localities, what's considered status consumption in a group of consumers
 still depends on the average group consumption.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The evidence for the relevance of a local reference level in status-related
 consumption (quality) has been substantial.
 Robert Frank
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "FrankPond"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, for example, finds that signaling needs become more important amongst
 the lower economic strata when they are huddled in the overpopulated suburban
 areas of big cities in the US.
 Similarly, Kaus
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "KausSA"
literal "true"

\end_inset

) and Chai et al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "ChaiKaus2019"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 present evidence that the conspicuous consumption for consumers in S Africa
 is relative to lower or similar income-groups (rather than relative to
 higher income groups).
 Even in contexts of food consumption, Sen
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sen2005Calories,DeatonDrezeIndiaFood"
literal "true"

\end_inset

